steps.prompt:
A feature request has been submitted for the {{target_release}} release.

Title: {{feature_title}}
Description: {{feature_description}}
Requester: {{requester}}
Priority: {{priority}}

Analyze this feature request and produce a structured triage assessment with the following labeled sections:
- impact_score: integer 1-10 (user value, business alignment, strategic fit)
- effort_score: integer 1-10 (engineering complexity, dependencies, risk; lower = less effort)
- recommendation: one of 'accept', 'defer', 'reject'
- rationale: 3-4 sentences explaining the scores and recommendation, noting any trade-offs or risks
- acceptance_criteria: 3-5 bullet points defining what 'done' looks like for this feature

Output plain text with labeled sections.

steps.notifyMsg:
Feature request deferred/rejected for {{target_release}}.

Feature: {{feature_title}}
Requester: {{requester}}
Impact score: {{steps.analyze-feature.output.impact_score}} | Effort score: {{steps.analyze-feature.output.effort_score}}
Recommendation: {{steps.analyze-feature.output.recommendation}}
Rationale: {{steps.analyze-feature.output.rationale}}

Consider resubmitting for a future release with additional context.

steps.prompt:
A new feature has been accepted for {{target_release}}.

Feature title: {{feature_title}}
Feature description: {{feature_description}}
Impact score: {{steps.analyze-feature.output.impact_score}}/10
Acceptance criteria: {{steps.analyze-feature.output.acceptance_criteria}}
Ticket ID: {{steps.create-ticket.output.ticket_id}}

Write polished, user-facing release notes for this feature. The tone should be enthusiastic but concise. Include:
1. A one-sentence headline (action-oriented, benefit-focused)
2. A short paragraph (50-80 words) explaining what changed and why users will love it
3. A 'How to use it' section with 2-3 bullet points

Do not use technical jargon. Write for end users, not engineers.

